<p><sup>*</sup>To achieve HA on storage, there are the following options:
</p>
<ul><li>For the Small size, it is recommended to use EFS . For performance consideration, you may choose NFS cluster that has multiple EBS volumes.</li>
<li>For larger sizes, you may use a NFS cluster that has multiple EBS volumes.</li></ul>
<p><sup>**</sup> The NFS volume sizes may grow on a daily basis. Check the Disk usage.
</p><p><sup>***</sup> For EBS backend storage, including EBS backended storage used for OS storage, EBS backended RDS services, you may switch to IO1 instead of GP2 for better performance. For more details, please find the guide for <a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://aws.amazon.com/ebs/details/">EBS storage</a> and <a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/UserGuide/CHAP_Storage.html">RDS Storage</a>.
</p><p><br>
</p>
<div class="Admonition_Note"><span class="autonumber">Note: </span>
<p>The values provided are the recommended minimum values. Components of Operations Bridge will scale, as needed, under performance load, without the need for manually adjusting these values. You may however assign more memory, processor, or storage resources as your workload increases. You can also increase the number of master or worker nodes to help further distribute the load.
</p>
</div>
